<paragraph blockId="10.[178,1085,613,875]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">
C o m m e n t: The original description is based on an unspecified number of 
<typeStatus box="[996,1085,613,634]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">syntypes</typeStatus>
from &quot;Kirdassah, 
<date box="[367,471,643,665]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" value="1933-09-28">28.9.1933</date>
; Sakkarah, 
<date box="[599,703,643,665]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" value="1933-09-15">15.9.1933</date>
; Pyramiden von Ghizeh, 
<date box="[980,1075,643,665]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" value="1933-10-02">2.X.1933</date>
&quot; (
<bibRefCitation author="KOCH C" box="[185,308,673,695]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" pagination="33 - 91" refId="ref6080" refString="KOCH C. (1934): Wissenschaftliche Ergebnisse der entomologischen Expeditionen seiner Durchlaucht des Fuersten Alessandro C. della Torre e Tasso nach Aegypten und auf die Halbinsel Sinai. IV. Staphylinidae (Coleoptera). - Bulletin de la Societe Royale Entomologique d'Egypte 1934: 33 - 91." type="journal article" year="1934">KOCH 1934</bibRefCitation>
). Five 
<typeStatus box="[376,467,674,695]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">syntypes</typeStatus>
, a male and 
<specimenCount box="[593,723,673,695]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" type="female">four females</specimenCount>
, were located in the Frey collection at the NHMB; the male is designated as the 
<typeStatus box="[629,725,703,725]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">lectotype</typeStatus>
. The Frey collection contains additional 
<specimenCount box="[243,358,733,755]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" type="female">six females</specimenCount>
from &quot;Sakkara&quot;. However, since the date of collection is not identical to that given in the original description, they cannot be considered types, although two of them had type labels attached to them. As can be inferred from the material studied by 
<bibRefCitation author="BORDONI A" box="[178,354,823,845]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" pagination="169 - 171" refId="ref5707" refString="BORDONI A. (1980): Studi sui Paederinae - VII - Sopra alcuni Hypomedon e Luzea poco noti (Col. Staphylinidae). - Redia 63: 169 - 171." type="journal article" year="1980">BORDONI (1980)</bibRefCitation>
, a male 
<typeStatus box="[456,535,824,845]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">syntype</typeStatus>
from &quot;Kirdassah&quot; and two non-type females from Kirdassah and Sakkara are deposited in the natural history museum in Milano.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[178,1085,891,1124]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">
The generic affiliations of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Koch" authorityYear="1934" box="[459,583,891,913]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Medon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="niloticus">
<emphasis box="[459,583,891,913]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">M. niloticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been a matter of controversy. Based on a study of a male 
<typeStatus box="[339,418,922,943]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">syntype</typeStatus>
and additional material, 
<bibRefCitation author="BORDONI A" box="[670,838,922,944]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" pagination="169 - 171" refId="ref5707" refString="BORDONI A. (1980): Studi sui Paederinae - VII - Sopra alcuni Hypomedon e Luzea poco noti (Col. Staphylinidae). - Redia 63: 169 - 171." type="journal article" year="1980">BORDONI (1980)</bibRefCitation>
attributed the species to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="MULSANT &amp; REY" authorityYear="1878" box="[178,300,952,974]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypomedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[178,300,952,974]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">Hypomedon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a generic name which at that time was interpreted differently and included the species today in 
<taxonomicName authority="STEPHENS 1829" authorityName="STEPHENS" authorityYear="1829" box="[384,621,982,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Sunius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[384,451,982,1004]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">Sunius</emphasis>
STEPHENS 1829
</taxonomicName>
. Four years later, 
<bibRefCitation author="COIFFAIT H" box="[803,971,982,1004]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" pagination="1 - 424" refId="ref5831" refString="COIFFAIT H. (1984): Coleopteres Staphylinidae de la region palearctique occidentale. V. Sous famille Paederinae Tribu Paederini 2, Sous famille Euaesthetinae. - Supplement a la Nouvelle Revue d'Entomologie 13 (4): 1 - 424." type="journal article" year="1984">COIFFAIT (1984)</bibRefCitation>
moved the species to 
<emphasis box="[289,412,1012,1034]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">Chloecharis</emphasis>
, which is now a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="MULSANT &amp; REY" authorityYear="1878" box="[803,925,1012,1034]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypomedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[803,925,1012,1034]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">Hypomedon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Subsequently, 
<bibRefCitation author="SMETANA A" box="[178,351,1042,1064]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" pagination="579 - 624" refId="ref6279" refString="SMETANA A. (2004): Subfamily Paederinae FLEMING, 1821. - In: LOBL I. &amp; A. SMETANA (eds), Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera. Volume 2. Hydrophiloidea - Histeroidea - Staphylinoidea. - Apollo Books, Stenstrup: 579 - 624." type="book chapter" year="2004">SMETANA (2004)</bibRefCitation>
attributed 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Koch" authorityYear="1934" box="[463,584,1042,1064]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Medon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="niloticus">
<emphasis box="[463,584,1042,1064]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">M. niloticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="STEPHENS" authorityYear="1829" box="[618,685,1042,1064]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Sunius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[618,685,1042,1064]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">Sunius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In a revision of the Western Palaearctic 
<taxonomicName box="[215,370,1072,1094]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Sunius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[215,282,1072,1094]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">Sunius</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="ASSING V" box="[385,552,1072,1094]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" pagination="5 - 135" refId="ref5601" refString="ASSING V. (2008 a): A revision of the Sunius species of the Western Palaearctic region and Middle Asia (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae). - Linzer biologische Beitrage 40 (1): 5 - 135." type="journal article" year="2008">ASSING (2008a)</bibRefCitation>
excluded it from the genus and transferred it to 
<emphasis box="[178,286,1102,1124]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">Cephisella</emphasis>
, primarily based on the figure of the aedeagus provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="BORDONI A" box="[891,1062,1102,1124]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" pagination="169 - 171" refId="ref5707" refString="BORDONI A. (1980): Studi sui Paederinae - VII - Sopra alcuni Hypomedon e Luzea poco noti (Col. Staphylinidae). - Redia 63: 169 - 171." type="journal article" year="1980">BORDONI (1980)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[178,1085,1140,1252]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">
An examination of the above 
<typeStatus box="[483,536,1141,1162]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">types</typeStatus>
and non-type specimens revealed that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Koch" authorityYear="1934" box="[939,1061,1140,1162]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Medon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="niloticus">
<emphasis box="[939,1061,1140,1162]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">M. niloticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is undoubtedly congeneric with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="WOLLASTON" baseAuthorityYear="1857" box="[486,738,1170,1192]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypomedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="debilicornis">
<emphasis box="[486,738,1170,1192]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">Hypomedon debilicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the 
<typeStatus box="[792,836,1171,1192]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">type</typeStatus>
species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="MULSANT &amp; REY" authorityYear="1878" box="[956,1078,1170,1192]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypomedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[956,1078,1170,1192]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">Hypomedon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="BORDONI" baseAuthorityYear="1980" box="[222,348,1200,1222]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypomedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="galilaeus">
<emphasis box="[222,348,1200,1222]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">H. galilaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The illustration of the aedeagus provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="BORDONI A" box="[827,992,1200,1222]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" pagination="169 - 171" refId="ref5707" refString="BORDONI A. (1980): Studi sui Paederinae - VII - Sopra alcuni Hypomedon e Luzea poco noti (Col. Staphylinidae). - Redia 63: 169 - 171." type="journal article" year="1980">BORDONI (1980</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation box="[1004,1076,1200,1222]" captionStart="Figs 1-7" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1471,1491]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,310,1443]" captionTargetId="figure-0@3.[178,1085,310,1462]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-7: Acanthoglossa orientis (FAUVEL) (1-3: lectotype of Cephisus orientis; 4-7: holotype of A. abeillei): (1, 4) habitus; (2, 5) forebody; (3, 6) aedeagus in lateral view; (7) male sternite VIII. Scale bars: 1, 4: 1.0 mm; 2, 5: 0.5 mm; 7: 0.2 mm; 3, 6: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5276551" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5276551/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">Fig. 1a</figureCitation>
) is highly misleading.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[178,1087,1268,1411]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">
D i a g n o s i s: Similarinexternalappearance(
<figureCitation box="[718,824,1268,1290]" captionStart="Figs 14-21" captionStartId="8.[178,218,1393,1413]" captionTargetBox="[183,1085,218,1368]" captionTargetId="figure-0@8.[178,1085,215,1385]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 14-21: Acanthoglossa punica FAUVEL from Chad (14-15), A. crassa COIFFAIT, holotype (16- 17), and Hypomedon niloticus (KOCH) (18-21): (14, 16, 18) habitus; (15, 17, 19) forebody; (20) male sternite VIII; (21) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 14, 16, 18: 1.0 mm; 15, 17, 19: 0.5 mm; 20-21: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5276557" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5276557/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">Figs18-19</figureCitation>
)to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="WOLLASTON" baseAuthorityYear="1857" box="[855,1008,1268,1290]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypomedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="debilicornis">
<emphasis box="[855,1008,1268,1290]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">H. debilicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="BORDONI" baseAuthorityYear="1980" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypomedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="galilaeus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">H. galilaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but distinguished from these species by smaller size and less pronounced microsculpture of head and pronotum, from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="BORDONI" baseAuthorityYear="1980" box="[669,801,1329,1351]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypomedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="galilaeus">
<emphasis box="[669,801,1329,1351]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">H. galilaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
additionally by the more transverse head, more pronounced hind angles of the head, as well as by larger and much more bulging eyes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[178,1087,1427,1479]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">
3: posterior margin of sternite VIII in the middle distinctly excised (more so than in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="BORDONI" baseAuthorityYear="1980" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypomedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="galilaeus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">H. galilaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (
<figureCitation box="[292,369,1457,1479]" captionStart="Figs 14-21" captionStartId="8.[178,218,1393,1413]" captionTargetBox="[183,1085,218,1368]" captionTargetId="figure-0@8.[178,1085,215,1385]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 14-21: Acanthoglossa punica FAUVEL from Chad (14-15), A. crassa COIFFAIT, holotype (16- 17), and Hypomedon niloticus (KOCH) (18-21): (14, 16, 18) habitus; (15, 17, 19) forebody; (20) male sternite VIII; (21) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 14, 16, 18: 1.0 mm; 15, 17, 19: 0.5 mm; 20-21: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5276557" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5276557/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
); aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[540,618,1457,1479]" captionStart="Figs 14-21" captionStartId="8.[178,218,1393,1413]" captionTargetBox="[183,1085,218,1368]" captionTargetId="figure-0@8.[178,1085,215,1385]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 14-21: Acanthoglossa punica FAUVEL from Chad (14-15), A. crassa COIFFAIT, holotype (16- 17), and Hypomedon niloticus (KOCH) (18-21): (14, 16, 18) habitus; (15, 17, 19) forebody; (20) male sternite VIII; (21) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 14, 16, 18: 1.0 mm; 15, 17, 19: 0.5 mm; 20-21: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5276557" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5276557/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">Fig. 21.</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[178,1011,1495,1517]" box="[178,1011,1495,1517]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1171">
D i s t r i b u t i o n: This species has become known only from 
